        Selling a Renovated Character Home in Brisbane Inner East 2026: How to Price the Premium
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A renovated Queenslander, Federation, post-war or character home does not price like a standard house. Here is how to identify the premium, find genuine comparables, and choose the right method of sale.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>You have spent two or three years and a meaningful sum of money renovating a character home in Brisbane's inner east. The kitchen is new. The bathrooms work. The roofline is intact, the VJ walls are restored, and the rear extension reads as if it has always been there. Now you are thinking about selling, and the first question is what the home is actually worth in 2026, and how to price it without leaving money on the table or scaring away the buyers who would pay the most for it.</p>

      <p>This article is for owners of renovated Queenslanders, Federation homes, interwar bungalows, post-war chamferboard cottages and other pre-1946 character homes in Bulimba, Hawthorne, Balmoral, Morningside, Norman Park, Camp Hill, Coorparoo and the surrounding inner east. The pricing logic for these homes is different from a renovated 1990s brick-and-tile, different from a new build, and different from a comparable character home on the same street that has not been touched. Most of the value in a renovated character home is sitting in the gap between what a generalist appraisal will tell you and what a specialist character buyer will actually pay. The job is to identify that gap, document it, and run a campaign that captures it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually pay extra for in a renovated character home</h2>
      <p>The premium that character buyers pay is not random. It tracks closely to a small list of features, and homes that score well on most of them outperform homes that score on only one or two. Knowing what is on this list shapes how you price and how you market.</p>

      <p>The first item is sympathetic restoration of original features. VJ walls, pressed metal ceilings, original timber floors (sanded and oiled rather than poly-coated), casement windows with their original hardware, original fireplaces, ornate ceiling roses and cornices, and intact verandah balustrades and brackets. Buyers paying the premium want to walk into a home that feels like the period it was built in, with the rough edges removed but the soul intact. Replacement of these features with modern substitutes typically reduces the premium even if the substitute looks similar at first glance.</p>

      <p>The second item is modern function behind the period facade. A well-designed kitchen with a butler's pantry, two or three bathrooms with proper waterproofing and decent storage, ducted air conditioning that has been threaded through the home without compromising ceiling height or original cornices, decent insulation, and updated electrical and plumbing. Buyers want to move in without immediately making a list of things to fix. The home needs to function as a 2026 family house while reading as a 1925 Queenslander.</p>

      <p>The third item is the quality and integration of any extension. The strongest results in the inner east go to homes where the rear extension respects the original roofline, uses materials that complement the original construction, preserves the back verandah or rebuilds it, and creates a single-level transition between the old and new sections rather than a jarring step-down or modern boxy addition jammed onto the back. A poorly designed extension can actively reduce value compared to the same home unextended, because the next buyer factors in the cost of removing or rebuilding it.</p>

      <p>The fourth item is the work underneath. Restumping (concrete or hardwood), subfloor moisture management, termite barriers, and proper drainage are not glamorous, but for an experienced character buyer they are evidence that the renovation has been done properly. A home with documented stump certification and a clean subfloor inspection has materially less perceived risk than one that looks beautiful upstairs but has unanswered questions below.</p>

      <p>The fifth item is street appeal. A repainted facade in a period-appropriate colour, a restored picket fence, a garden that lets the architecture breathe, and a verandah that reads as habitable space rather than a passageway. Character buyers in Brisbane's inner east will often drive past a home twice before they book an inspection, and the facade is the deciding factor for many of them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers do not pay extra for</h2>
      <p>Just as important is what does not earn a premium. Renovations that lose the character buyer pool can also fail to attract the modern buyer pool, leaving the home stranded between markets.</p>

      <p>Over-modernisation is the most common mistake. White-painted VJ walls under a thick coat of plaster, original timber floors covered in laminate, exposed beams boxed in, fireplaces removed or sealed, and original windows replaced with aluminium sliders. Each of these decisions removes a feature that the character buyer was specifically prepared to pay for. Some of them can be reversed, but the buyer who notices an aluminium window where a casement should be will mentally discount the home before they have walked through the front door.</p>

      <p>Heritage-incompatible additions are the second mistake. A flat-roofed first-floor pop-up that breaks the silhouette of the original roofline, a rear addition in materials that clash with the original construction, or a deck and pool layout that consumes the back garden without considering the relationship to the house. Brisbane City Council's Traditional Building Character (design) overlay code in City Plan 2014 specifically guides extensions and new builds to complement the character of the surrounding street, and homes that have been extended outside that guidance are often homes that were extended without development approval, which becomes a disclosure issue at sale time. (Source: <a href="https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/building-and-planning/getting-started-on-your-project/heritage-properties" style="color:#b98229;">Brisbane City Council, Heritage and character properties</a>.)</p>

      <p>Excessive personalisation is the third. A renovation that reflects very specific tastes, such as a heavily themed colour palette, unusual joinery details or highly customised built-ins, narrows the buyer pool. Character buyers are willing to pay for craft and quality, but most of them want the option to make the home their own. The closer the renovation sits to a confident, period-respectful neutral, the wider the buyer pool and the higher the realised price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to find genuine comparables</h2>
      <p>Standard comparable sales analysis fails for renovated character homes because the data set is wide and noisy. To get a useful number, the comparable filter needs to be tighter than the default.</p>

      <p>Start with the overlay and zone. A home inside the Traditional Building Character overlay or the Character Residential zone is in a different market to a similar-aged home outside it, because the demolition rules in City Plan 2014 protect the streetscape and the buyer pool factors that into their offer. The Planning and Environment Court has approved demolition of pre-1947 dwellings only where the home is found not to contribute to traditional building character, which is a high bar. (Source: <a href="https://urpec.com.au/tbc-overlay/" style="color:#b98229;">Urpec, Traditional Building Character overlay explained</a>.) For a deeper read on the overlay specifically, see the article on <a href="/insights/traditional-building-character-overlay-pre-1947-brisbane-sellers" style="color:#b98229;">the TBC overlay for pre-1947 sellers</a>.</p>

      <p>Filter by renovation level next. Group sales into three tiers: unrenovated or original condition, partially renovated (one or two rooms updated), and fully renovated to a contemporary standard. A fully renovated Queenslander does not compare to an unrenovated one, even if they are on the same street and the same land size. The price gap between the two tiers in suburbs like Bulimba and Hawthorne can be several hundred thousand dollars, sometimes more.</p>

      <p>Filter by recency. Renovated character home pricing has moved meaningfully over the last twenty-four months, with Norman Park houses showing a 10.8% annual lift to a $1.6M median in late 2025 (Source: <a href="https://www.harcourtssolutions.com.au/suburb-profiles/norman-park-qld-4170/" style="color:#b98229;">Harcourts Solutions, Norman Park profile</a>) and Coorparoo at a $1.482M median (Source: <a href="https://auhouseprices.com/suburb/profile/QLD/4151/Coorparoo/" style="color:#b98229;">AuHousePrices, Coorparoo profile</a>). Use sales from the last six months for the strongest signal. Sales from twelve months ago are useful as context, but they are not the price guide.</p>

      <p>Filter by land size, aspect and position. A 405 square metre block on a quiet street in Hawthorne is not the same as a 600 square metre block on a busier road, even if both homes are similarly renovated. Land content carries more weight in character home pricing than in townhouse or apartment pricing, because the buyer is buying the option to extend, pool or landscape.</p>

      <ResourceCTA slug="comparable-sales-worksheet" />

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing strategy: auction, private treaty, or Expressions of Interest</h2>
      <p>The choice of method of sale matters more for a renovated character home than for most other property types, because the buyer pool behaves differently and the price discovery problem is harder.</p>

      <p>Auction tends to work well in inner east streets with limited stock where the buyer pool is deep, the home is genuinely emotional (intact original features, sought-after street, walkable to a village strip or school), and recent auction clearance for character homes in the immediate area has been strong. The auction format compresses the negotiation into a single afternoon and uses competitive bidding to move the price beyond what any individual buyer would have offered in a private negotiation. In a competitive auction, two committed character buyers can push the result above the comparable sales benchmark by a meaningful margin.</p>

      <p>Private treaty suits homes where the buyer pool is smaller or more discerning, the renovation is architecturally specific, or the price guidance is in the upper range of the suburb and needs more time to find the right buyer. Private treaty also gives the seller more control over the negotiation and allows for conditional offers that can sometimes deliver a better result than a forced auction-day price.</p>

      <p>Expressions of Interest is a useful middle ground for higher-end renovated character homes, particularly architecturally designed properties on premium streets. EOI campaigns invite written offers by a deadline, then negotiate with the strongest buyers individually. This approach captures the urgency of an auction without the public risk of passing in. It also suits buyers who are uncomfortable bidding publicly but are prepared to commit at the right level.</p>

      <p>The right method is the one that fits the home and the buyer pool, not the one the agent prefers by default. For a longer discussion of how character homes are typically marketed and which buyer pools they attract, see the original article on <a href="/insights/selling-queenslander-character-home-brisbane" style="color:#b98229;">selling a Queenslander or character home in Brisbane</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Documentation that supports the premium</h2>
      <p>A renovated character home priced at a premium needs the documentation to back the price. Buyers paying above the suburb benchmark are paying for certainty, and certainty comes from paperwork.</p>

      <p>The core pack should include the builder and architect details for the renovation, with contact details where possible. Materials and finishes lists matter, particularly for kitchens, bathrooms, joinery and any heritage-compatible imports. Council approvals for any structural work, including the rear extension and any first-floor additions. Any TBC overlay approvals or evidence that the work was within accepted development. A current building and pest inspection, ideally from a Brisbane inspector who works regularly with character homes. An asbestos register where the home has any pre-1990 fabric. Restumping or stump certification where the home has been raised or restumped. Electrical and plumbing compliance certificates. Energy efficiency information and any insulation details.</p>

      <p>For homes that fall under any heritage listing or the Character Residential zone, additional records help. The original construction date, where it can be verified through Queensland State Archives or council records. Photographs from before the renovation that show what was preserved. Records of any heritage-compatible joinery or hardware sourced from specialist suppliers. The deeper context on how heritage and character listings work in Brisbane is set out in the article on <a href="/insights/heritage-overlays-brisbane" style="color:#b98229;">heritage overlays in Brisbane</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing the renovation honestly without underselling the period appeal</h2>
      <p>The marketing of a renovated character home walks a narrow line. Lean too hard on the modern renovation and the character buyer thinks the home has lost its soul. Lean too hard on the period detail and the modern family thinks they will need to do more work than they can stomach. The best campaigns hold both at once.</p>

      <p>The photography matters more than for a standard listing. Character homes need natural light, considered angles that show the relationship between original features and modern updates, and a photographer who understands how to make warm timber tones read as inviting. The hero image is usually the facade or the verandah, not the kitchen.</p>

      <p>The copywriting should name the period and the original features specifically. "1924 Queenslander" reads more credibly than "character home". "Original VJ walls and pressed metal ceilings" reads more credibly than "period charm". Specificity is what convinces character buyers that the home is the real thing rather than a homage to it.</p>

      <p>The campaign should reach the buyer pool where they actually look. Domain and realestate.com.au still drive most of the inquiries, but for higher-priced renovated character homes the pre-market and database work matters more. Many of the strongest results for character homes in the inner east come from buyers who knew about the property before the listing went live, because the agent had relationships with the buyers in the suburb who were specifically watching for the right home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical 2026 sequence for owners thinking about selling</h2>
      <p>For owners in this position now, the sequence that tends to deliver the strongest result starts with appraisal, not advertising. Get a written appraisal that breaks the price into components: the land value, the value of the original character features, the value of the renovation work, and the value of any extensions or improvements. An appraisal that does not show this breakdown is not telling you enough.</p>

      <p>Next, gather the documentation pack. Aim to have it ready before the campaign launches rather than scrambling for it during due diligence. The strongest negotiating position is one where every reasonable buyer question has a documented answer.</p>

      <p>Then choose the method of sale based on the buyer pool depth in your specific suburb and street, not on a generic preference. Look at recent auction clearance for character homes within walking distance, not the suburb-wide number.</p>

      <p>Finally, plan the campaign around the buyer pool you actually have. For most renovated character homes in the inner east, that is a mix of established Brisbane families upgrading from a modern home into character, interstate buyers relocating from Sydney and Melbourne, and downsizers from larger acreage moving back into the city. Each of these segments responds to slightly different messaging, and the campaign should be specific enough to speak to all three.</p>

